### ğŸ’§ Waterfall Model (in Software)

In the early days, software teams followed the **Waterfall model**.

- Client gives full requirements upfront and a **1-year deadline**
- Developers think: _â€œWe have timeâ€_ and delay coding
- After 6 months, they start writing code
- Development takes 3 months
- Testing team gets the code with only 2 months left
- They find 10 defects
- Developer says: _â€œI wrote this 3 months ago! I forgot the logic!â€_

ğŸ˜¡ Blame game begins:

- Developers blame testers  
- Testers blame developers  

ğŸ’¥ **Client expected a Ferrari, but got an Alto 800.**

Clearly, something had to change...

---

## ğŸ” Agile Model (in Software)

Companies started caring more about clients and adopted **Agile**, using **sprints**.

### ğŸ§© Example Modules:

- Signup & Login  
- Product Management  
- Order Management  
- Shipping  
- Payments  
- Reviews  

### ğŸš€ Sprint-1: (2 weeks to 1 month)

- Client: â€œI need the **Signup & Login** module this month.â€
- Developer takes 15 days to code it
- During that time, testers wait (idle)
- Once ready, code goes to testers
- Testers take a week â†’ Find 2 bugs
- Developer fixes them

âœ… Module is ready by month-end.

ğŸ”„ If the client suggests changes, they go to the **Sprint-2 backlog** â€” along with the next module (e.g., Product Management).

ğŸ“Œ **Client expected a Ferrari, got a Honda City** â€” decent and delivered.

